Does the news predict the stock market or simply report on it?

Eric Robertson

Overview¶

What is the aim of this project?¶

Its always a go-to data science question of using news data to predict stock price. I myself have gone through that activity multiple times, but the underlying assumption is that in some way news about stocks predicts price of stock. I wanted to examine that trend more. Youtube specificly has a large collection of independent financial channels on youtube who report on many stock trends and often make reccomendations about what stocks to buy and what they are investing in. These communities have sprung up noteably over the last few years and Id recon they have a decent amount of swing on the market as a whole. My goal is to explore this relationship and see how so-called hot stocks are formed and possibly predict them.

What value does this project actually provide?¶

Certainly stock prediction is devorced from a lot of value that other datasets may provide, but in this example it will be a good chance to look more into the news cycle and how the naritave produces by news (specificly those on youtube) is influenced by outside factors. What causes the naritave to change and how does the naritave influence the world outside of it.

What data and tools are used for the project?¶

Youtube has a very active group of independent financial / stock channels which follow stocks and often publish frequently about financial news. Using the Youtube video api we will be collecting a large collection of recent video information and using it to coorlate with daily stock data over the last few years.

Youtube Youtube channels for this dataset were hand chosen by me due to youtubes lack of robust ability to objectively rank chanel views and cataglories. This certainly adds some bias into the data and results, but I will explore that more as I move throught the project.

Stocks Stocks to compair channels with were also hand selected, but I aimed to incorperate a broad range of stocks to help with analysis. This also produces bias, but the hope is that with a large enough collection I am able to produce a good sample of results.

# Examining API

def youtube_api_parse ( response ) :
    return json.loads(response.text.encode("ascii", "ignore").decode("utf-8"))['items']

def youtube_api_search_for_channel ( channel_search ):
    return youtube_api_parse(
        requests.get( f"{youtube_api_base}/search?part=id%2Csnippet&q={channel_search}&type=channel&key={youtube_api_keys[_key]}"))

# Specificly we want youtube videos and their metadata though

# Search for a channel id given name
def youtube_api_channelID ( channel_search ):
    return youtube_api_search_for_channel( channel_search )[0]['id']['channelId']
    
# Get video ids given channel id
def youtube_api_videoIDs ( channel_id ):
    results = youtube_api_parse(
        requests.get( f"{youtube_api_base}/search?key={youtube_api_keys[_key]}&channelId={channel_id}&part=snippet,id&order=date&maxResults=20"))
    video_ids = [ a['id']['videoId'] for a in results if a['id']['kind'] == 'youtube#video' ]
    return video_ids

# Get video meta data given video id
def youtube_api_videoMeta ( video_id ):
    return youtube_api_parse(
        requests.get( f"{youtube_api_base}/videos?part=snippet,statistics&id={video_id}&key={youtube_api_keys[_key]} "))
    
# Pull it all together
def youtube_api_load_videos ( channel_search ):
    channelID = youtube_api_channelID( channel_search )
    videoIDs = youtube_api_videoIDs( channelID )
    
    return youtube_api_videoMeta ( videoIDs [0]  )

def alphavantage_load_stock ( stock ) : 
    response = requests.get(f"https://www.alphavantage.co/query?function=TIME_SERIES_DAILY_ADJUSTED&symbol={stock}&apikey={alphavantage_api}&outputsize=full")
    return json.loads( response.text )

# Package it up for easy consumption
def download_stock ( stock ):
    outfile = f"stock_data/{stock}.json"
    if os.path.exists(outfile): return
    stock_data = alphavantage_load_stock( stock )
    with open(outfile, 'w') as outfile:
        outfile.write(json.dumps(stock_data))
    print(f"Loaded {len(stock_data['Time Series (Daily)'])} days of data for {stock}".ljust(100,' '))

# Both the stock data any youtube data in its current form is hard to work with, cleaning it up into cleaner tables to be used later
# Cleaning up youtube videos first

def load_video_paths ( channel ):
    path = f"./youtube_data/{channel}"
    return [ f"{path}/videos/{_}" for _ in os.listdir(f"{path}/videos") ]

def load_video_data ( video_path ):
    return util.load_json( video_path )
    
def pullValue ( data, value, default ):
    return data[value] if value in data else default

# Clean up the video
def extract_video_data ( data ):
    
    response = {}
    videoData = data['items'][0]
    snippet  = videoData['snippet']
    
    response['id'] = videoData['id']
    response['date'] = snippet['publishedAt'][:10]
    response['title'] = snippet['title']
    response['description'] = snippet['description']
    response['channelTitle'] = snippet['channelTitle']
    response['tags'] = pullValue( snippet, 'tags', ['untagged'])
    response['views'] = pullValue( videoData['statistics'], 'viewCount', 0) 
    response['likes'] = pullValue( videoData['statistics'], 'likeCount', 0)
    response['dislikes'] =  pullValue( videoData['statistics'], 'dislikeCount', 0)
    response['commentCount'] = pullValue( videoData['statistics'], 'commentCount', 0)
    
    return response

Stock Data¶

In [16]:
# For this dataset we really only care about the stock data for the last 3 years and the closing prices
def process_stocks () :
    
    prices = []
    index_loaded = False
    
    for stock in target_stocks:
        # Taking only the daily data from the last few years
        frame = pd.DataFrame(util.load_json( f'./stock_data/{stock}.json' )['Time Series (Daily)']).T 
        frame = frame[ frame.index > '2017-01-01']

        # Taking only the close price
        frame = frame['5. adjusted close']
        prices.append( frame )

    clean_stocks = pd.DataFrame(prices).T
    clean_stocks.columns = target_stocks
    clean_stocks.to_csv( f"./stock_data/clean.csv" )
    
    return clean_stocks

Video Tags¶

Now, to explore how trends are changing over time, lets look at popularities of various tags over the dataset. Just because a tag shows up, doesnt mean it actually has engagement or reach. To help judge the reach of a particular tag, ill be weighting various metrics. More information can be seen here: https://blog.hootsuite.com/calculate-engagement-rate/ as to how / why I chose what i did

The intent of this analysis is to see how videos and stocks coorilate. The connection there is that videos sway popular opinion or on other ways are a product of it. Thus, we dont care about the specific quantity of videos, but the social impact of each video. How much did each video impact the collective conscious. Thats a hard question, but one aproach is to measure its engagement for a stand in for popularity.

Below I give each video a weight that represents how impactful the video was. It is calculated by:

weight = views + net likes 20 + comments 100

The rational is that likes indicate higher engagement than just views, and comments even more engagement. Certainly these weights can be adjusted but this is what will be used as weight of a video for this project.

In [23]:
# Process tag data
def generate_tag_representation () :
    tag_data = []
    for channel in target_channels:
        data = pd.read_csv( f"./youtube_data/{channel}/clean.cvs" )
        for i,row in data.iterrows():
            # Weight the tags basted on engagement
            weight = row['views'] + (row['likes'] - row['dislikes']) * 20 + row['commentCount'] * 100
            for tag in ast.literal_eval(row['tags']):
                tag_data.append(( row['date'], row['channelTitle'], row['id'], tag, weight ))
        print(f"{channel} loaded".ljust(100,' '), end='\r')

    # Merge into data frame
    tag_data = pd.DataFrame(tag_data, columns=['date', 'channel', 'vid', 'tag', 'weight'] )
    
    # Clean up the tags for later use
    tag_data['tag'] = tag_data['tag'].str.replace(r'[^A-Za-z]', '').str.lower()
    
    # Save back out
    tag_data.to_csv( f"./youtube_data/tag_view.csv" )

Normalization¶

We have much more organized data so far, but its still quite skewed for various reasons. Lets explore why and see if we can correct them.

Tags by day¶

# See how the weight per-day is skewed forward
def plot_normalization_chart ( data, title = "" ):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    plt.plot( data)
    ax.set(title=title, xlabel='date', ylabel='Weight')
    fig.set_size_inches(18,7)
    
_ = tag_representation.groupby('date').sum()
plot_normalization_chart( _.weight, title="Non-normalized tag weights by day")

Above it is clear that the weight of the tags are rising with time, in part because we have more samples for closer dates. To alleviate this we can divide by the number of videos published each day to help remove the bias from more videos being produced. In addition, the number of videos published from ealier dates is so few that many days lack video data at all. To help with this, we can fill any null date with 0s or remove them from the data set.

In [31]:
# Since some days dont have data to report, lets fill them with 0s for now
def fill_empty_dates (df):
    dates = pd.date_range(df.index.min(), df.index.max())
    return df.reindex(dates)

We are still running into issues though, certainly if we get a viral video followed by a gap in the dataset we find a huge skew. However, leaving days with 0s really doesnt help because when we consider video data, its not just the day in quesiton but the effect of the video persists afterwards as people dont all watch it on the day it was released. Exploring what others have done with this problem, it seems video videos views exponantially fall off from the initial date it was published. here is an explanation if you want to see more.

In the above graph we are trying to measure the impact of various videos over time, but the video doesnt instantly get all its viewers. Analysis by others show that it quickly peeks and then falls off with an exponentially decaying curve after its been published. To augment our data, lets see if we can replicate this exponential decay to help better understand video impact over time.

Smoothing data with expontial decay¶

In [37]:
# Utilities for smoothing

# Utility to shift an array by a given number
def shift(xs, n):
    e = np.empty_like(xs)
    if n >= 0:
        e[:n] = 0
        e[n:] = xs[:-n]
    else:
        e[n:] = 0
        e[:n] = xs[-n:]
    return e

# Smoothing attempts
def smooth_exponent ( data, d = 2 ):
    out = data.astype(np.float32)
    for i in range( 1, d ):
        out += (shift(data, i)/(i+1)).astype(np.float32)
    return scale ( out )
def smooth_rolling ( data, d = 5 ):
    return scale ( 
        pd.Series(data)
            .rolling(d).mean()
            .rolling(d*2).mean()
            .fillna(0)
    )
def smooth_rolling_bidirection ( data, d = 5 ):
    return scale ( 
        pd.Series(data)
            .rolling(d).mean()[::-1]
            .rolling(d).mean()[::-1]
            .rolling(d*2).mean()[::-1]
            .rolling(d*2).mean()[::-1]
            .fillna(0)
    )

# Scale all the data so it is between 0 and 1
def scale ( data ):
    return (data - data.min()) / ( data.max() - data.min() )
In [38]:
# Testing it out on some fake data
fake_data = np.random.choice(3, 100, p=[0.85, 0.075, 0.075])

_scaled = scale( fake_data )
_exponential = smooth_exponent ( fake_data, d = 20 )
_rolling = smooth_rolling( fake_data, d=5 )
_rolling_bi = smooth_rolling_bidirection( fake_data, d=2 )
_exponential_rolling = smooth_rolling_bidirection( _exponential, d=1 )

fig, ax = plt.subplots(5,1)
ax[0].plot( _scaled ); ax[0].set(title="Fake Data")
ax[1].plot( _exponential ); ax[1].set(title="Exponential Smoothing")
ax[2].plot( _rolling ); ax[2].set(title="Rolling Smoothing")
ax[3].plot( _rolling_bi ); ax[3].set(title="Rolling Bidirection Smoothing")
ax[4].plot( _exponential_rolling ); ax[4].set(title="Exponential + Rolling")
fig.set_size_inches(21,20)

The above visualizaiton can help see what effects the smoothing techniques will have on the data. Exponsntial smoothing seems to mimich the observed behaviour of video views the closest, which would be highly advantagous. But at the same time it seems to make the data more rough, which is not helpful. Rolling smoothing smoothes out the data somewhat, but also shifts the events forward in time, meaing relational time data is somewhat lost. Doing a bi-direction rolling average corrects this time-shifting, but also allows some data to blead back in time which can give false results considering this is a time-seriese data comparison. Finally, in an atempt to get the best of both worlds, combining exponential with a small bi-direction rolling cuts drasticly down on the spikeyness of the data while not flattening it out as much as pure bi-direction. Lets use this for the analysis.

In [39]:
# The final smoothing analysis
def smooth_time_data ( data ):
    return smooth_rolling_bidirection( smooth_exponent( data, d=20 ), d=2 )

# First, lets use the smoothing data we established before to look at a few tags over time
def get_performance ( _tag, start='2017-01-03', end='2020-12-05'):
    tag = _tag
    tag = tag_representation[ tag_representation.tag == tag ].groupby('date').sum().sort_index()
    tag = fill_empty_dates( tag ).fillna(0)
    tag['total_weight'] = daily_weight['weight']
    tag['share_of_weight'] = tag['weight'] / tag['total_weight']
    tag['smoothed_weight'] = smooth_time_data( tag['share_of_weight'] )
    tag = clamp_dates(tag.dropna(), start = start, end=end).fillna(0)
    return tag['smoothed_weight']

def clamp_dates (df, start='2017-01-01', end='2020-12-05'):
    dates = pd.date_range(start, end)
    return df.reindex(dates)

# It would be really good if we could further understand this relation with a numerical measure, a good one is the pearson measure
_labels = ['tsla','teslastock','coronavirus','covid']
_tags = [a,b,c,d]
results = []

for tag1 in _tags:
    row = []
    for tag2 in _tags:
        first = max( tag1[tag1>0].index[0], tag2[tag2>0].index[0] )
        
        # Taking the diff here because we care about reletive movement and not absolute values
        _a = tag1[tag1.index >= first ].diff().dropna()
        _b = tag2[tag2.index >= first ].diff().dropna()
        
        # Calculate pearsonr value for the pair of seriese
        row.append(stats.pearsonr(_a,_b)[0])
    results.append(row)

# Utility function to compair a stock and a tag
def compair_stock_to_tag ( tag, stock ):
    rolling = 10

    _stock = stocks[stock].sort_index()
    _stock.index = pd.to_datetime(_stock.index)
    _stock = scale(_stock).rolling(rolling).sum()

    _tag = get_performance(tag).sort_index()
    _tag = scale(_tag)
    _tag = _tag.rolling(rolling).sum()

    _combined = pd.DataFrame([_stock, _tag]).T.dropna()
    _stock = _combined[ _combined.columns[0] ]
    _tag = _combined[ _combined.columns[1] ]

    return stats.pearsonr(_stock,_tag)[0], _stock, _tag

This chart above represents what may be a stock data from the market and a youtube data tag listing. We are aiming to understand a given youtube trend is a real prediction / influence on stock price or if it simply is a report on price changes. IE: Does youtube trends predict stock trends or simply mirror them. One way to assess this relationship is to compair how well a coorilation data forms at various shifts. Below I illistrate this more.

In [162]:
# Define
def run_shift_similarity( data, n ):
    if n == 0:
        return 1
    else:
        a = data.fillna(0)
        b = shift(a, n)
        return stats.pearsonr(a,b)[0]

sims = []
for i in range(-20,20):
    _ = run_shift_similarity(fake_data, i)
    sims.append( _  )
    
plt.plot(range(-20,20), sims)
plt.title('Coorilation given various degrees of shift')
plt.xlabel('Amount graph shifted')
plt.ylabel('Level Of Coorilation')
fig.set_size_inches(15,8)

In this graph we can see the various levels of coorilation observed from a simple shift of one curve when compaired with itself. As the graph shifts to one side and then is compaired to the un-shifted version, it becomes a worse and worse match over time as illistrated above with 0 being the highest value. We can use this to test relation between stocks and tags. If we shift the tag graph to the right and the coorilation increases, we can see evidence that the tag is actively predicting the stock data. Similarly if we shift it left and gain coorilation then we gain evidence for a simple mirror of the stock price rather than active anticipation.

In [163]:
# Implementing a forward and backward shift algorithm
def compair_stock_to_tag_with_shift ( tag, stock ):
    rolling = 10
    shift_amount = 15

    _stock = stocks[stock].sort_index()
    _stock.index = pd.to_datetime(_stock.index)
    _stock = scale(_stock).rolling(rolling).sum()

    _tag = get_performance(tag).sort_index()
    _tag = scale(_tag)
    _tag = _tag.rolling(rolling).sum()

    _combined = pd.DataFrame([_stock, _tag]).T.dropna()
    _stock = _combined[ _combined.columns[0] ]
    _tag = _combined[ _combined.columns[1] ]
    
    
    shift_back_score = stats.pearsonr(_stock, shift(_tag, -shift_amount))[0]
    plain_score = stats.pearsonr(_stock, _tag)[0]
    shift_forward_score = stats.pearsonr(_stock, shift(_tag, +shift_amount))[0]

    return shift_back_score, plain_score, shift_forward_score

# Do that shift for each item in the dataset

    _stock_name = stocks.columns[i]
    results.append( compair_stock_to_tag_with_shift( _stock_tag, _stock_name ))

Conclusion¶

What did we learn?¶

There is a lot of take away here. First, we gained more of an understanding of how stocks coorilate with tags. Certain stocks are seemingly highly coorilated while others are simply ignored. This mirrors the youtube community as a whole as certain stocks become hot stocks and get lots of attention while others are never picked up. This small list of hot stocks acounts for the majority of coorilation we saw expressed. Furthermore, we found that these coorilations were not particularly likely to predict actual stock movements in any useful way. For the most part our final results found that it was very much a mixed bag on what could be classified as a predictor vs a reporter.

What complications were run into?¶

For the most part, a lack of data. With a quarter million tags over four years, i had hoped for more a clear outcome but the data was still much to noisy. For all but a few stocks, there simply was not enough data to make an impact. Further data could be scraped with more time but as it is currently more infromation can not really be pulled from what was found.

Extentions?¶

NLP models could be deployed to help further give a better weight for each tag. Other sources like comments or captions for videos could be further deployed. In general, more stocks could be coorilated with more tags and more relations found.
